PROMPT oracle_bone_pictographic_evolution
WITH BUDGET 6000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a Chinese paleography and historical linguistics expert specializing in the evolution of Chinese writing systems, with deep expertise in oracle bone script development and the transformation of pictographic characters into abstract forms.")

GENERATE
    explain_pictographic_evolution("Explain why pictographic characters in oracle bone script evolved into more abstract forms. Cover: 1) The practical constraints of carving into hard materials like turtle shells and ox bones that made simple geometric strokes more efficient than detailed pictographic representations, requiring scribes to simplify complex visual forms into essential linear elements that could be quickly and reliably carved, 2) The standardization pressures as oracle bone script became more widely used across the Shang administrative system, necessitating consistent character forms that different scribes could reproduce uniformly rather than individualistic pictographic interpretations, 3) The influence of writing tools and techniques, where bronze knives and carving implements naturally produced angular, straight-line strokes rather than the curved organic forms of true pictographs, leading to geometric simplification of originally naturalistic images, 4) The speed requirements of administrative and ritual record-keeping, where scribes needed to write quickly during divination ceremonies and governmental documentation, making abstract abbreviated forms more practical than time-consuming detailed pictures, 5) The conceptual shift from representing concrete objects to expressing abstract ideas and grammatical relationships, requiring characters to function as linguistic symbols rather than mere pictures, thus driving the development of more systematic and abstract visual conventions, 6) Specific examples of this evolution showing how characters like 日 (sun), 月 (moon), 水 (water), 火 (fire), 人 (person), and 馬 (horse) transformed from recognizable pictographs in early oracle bone script to increasingly schematic and abstract forms, demonstrating the progression from direct visual representation to symbolic notation, 7) The role of frequency of use, where commonly written characters underwent more rapid simplification due to repeated copying, while rarely used characters retained more pictographic elements longer, 8) How this abstractization process laid the foundation for the systematic development of Chinese characters as a mature writing system capable of expressing complex linguistic structures beyond simple object representation, 9) The relationship between visual economy and semantic efficiency, where abstract forms allowed for faster recognition and writing while maintaining clear semantic distinctions, 10) How this evolutionary pattern reflects broader principles of writing system development found across world scripts, where practical usage pressures consistently drive the simplification of complex visual symbols into efficient abstract notation systems.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 3000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.1, FORMAT markdown;